Citizen.Name: GEARY, KATHLEEN
Description: 359 Somerville Avenue houses apartments AND a commercial entity, Bombay Market.  The backyard and structure is simply overrun with rats.  On a daily basis we have watched 5-10 rats at a time go right into the structure through a hole at the back of the market, which serves produce for human consumption.  The backyard is a total mess, with a dead tree (that we have separately requested be removed due to the safety risk) contributing to heavy underbrush, and open containers of trash in the yard and immediately inside the open door to the market where we have seen the rats enter.  Our backyard faces theirs, and though we've tried numerous alternatives to keep the rats out (wire netting around our fence, all trash totally sealed), it is simply not safe to walk out there anymore.   There are children in the surrounding apartments, not to mention customers of the market unaware of the issue, and this has become a major health risk!

Citizen.Name: GAFFNEY, LESLIE
Description: We have complained about rats before, which has resulted into two of our adjacent neighbors to clean up their back yard.  However, the 446 Broadway backyard is a complete mess with trash bags, broken glass, building materials, discarded furniture, rotting carpet, etc. We see rats in this backyard all the time and have the feeling that they are living in the concrete block garage. The door into this garage is always askew and we see rats go in and out. Yesterday we saw a few rats chase a squirrel out of this backyard in broad day light.  We actually have this chase on video, and also took a number of pictures to illustrate the mess in the 464 Broadway backyard. In the meantime I have caught about 40 to 50 rats so far using rat snap traps and peanut butter. I wish the city could come out to bait the neighboring property with a strong and efficient poison.  Regards, Frank van den Elzen and Leslie Gaffney octafish@rcn.com

Comment: 11/23/11 I left door knockers on all addresses and spoke to the people at the Tufts Houses on Professors Row.
Description: In a previous report, I mistakenly said there was no construction nearby. The rat problem began during Tufts University's massive construction projects (tennis courts) and house renovations (Professors Row). When they rebuilt the tennis courts and repaired the stone wall on Packard Ave, rats living in the stone wall (between the courts & the president's house) moved into the stone wall outside 114 Professors Row, the wall belonging to 134 Professors Row (on Curtis Avenue), and under porches on Curtis Ave (#s 15, 14-16, 18-20, 22-24). Although the dumpster belonging to #134 Professors Row is screened from public view, garbage is not always properly disposed of there, nor at #15 Curtis Ave. I see that my last ticket item was closed, but the problem has NOT been resolved--the rats are still active in all these locations. Please distribute notices to residences on Curtis Ave and notify Tufts University of the problem, request compliance with trash ordinances, and lay out poison and/or traps where possible. Thnx

Description: I'm submitting this 311 report at the request of Ellen Schneider. We've been working with her and Frank Keohane on an ongoing rodent problem we've been having with the property that abuts ours (ours is 31 Mansfield, and the abutting properties are 282 and 280 McGrath Highway). About two months ago they removed a rusted out car that was harboring rats and a month ago they cleaned up debris and an exterminator baited the property, and we thought that had taken car of the rats. But unfortunately, earlier this week we discovered two large rat holes in our yard just over the property boundary, which have appeared after we leveled and re-seeded our yard three weekends ago. Frank had said that we've done everything we possibly can on our end to ensure the rats aren't coming from our property, so there must still be an ongoing problem from the abutting property or from another nearby property. Any assistance would be appreciated!

Description: Last Friday evening, around 9:30 pm, we discovered a rat in our kitchen and after attempting to contact Somerville Animal Control (they were closed at the time), we called a local exterminator to come remove it from our house. We've informed our landlord of the problem and asked that they reimburse us for the $165 fee paid to the exterminator, as well as to take additional preventative measures to ensure that no further infestations occur. Unfortunately, our landlords are not fluent in English, and communicating with them is quite difficult. They are saying that they do not want to pay the fee and they have their own solution to the rat problem. In the past, when we found mice in our apartment, they told us to get a cat. We subsequently solved the problem using rat poison, which we paid for ourselves. My roommate, who paid the extermination fee, offered to deduct it from her rent check next month, but the landlords have deemedthis unacceptable. We are not sure how to proceed.

Citizen.Name: PAULSON, ANDREA
Description: My property abuts the Somerville municipal parking lot (near Downtown Liquors)  also the back entrance (and dumpster) of Out of the Blue, Spikes Junkyard Dogs and the Painted Burro. Many rats in the Dresden Circle residential area about 4 weeks ago. Neighbors joined to hire an exterminator, at our own expense, for 3 weeks now. The number of reported rats decreased in the last week, but still evidence of rodents. There is a dumpster behind these restaurants in the City parking lot which is habitually left open. At times, the trash bags fall out of the dumpster to the ground. I have taken photos of this, 4 times, on 16, 21, 23 & 25 Sept. I would like the City to enforce the rodent prevention ordinances for this dumpster. We the neighbors are scrupulous about keeping our trash bins closed tight. It is frustrating that we must shell out $500+ on rodent control when our efforts will be useless (and $ wasted) if the City does not enforce the rodent control ordinances for the restaurants in the area.

Description: The reason I am writing to you instead of calling 311 is because I feel very frustrated and nothing is being done about the huge rodent problem that we are experiencing in Somerville for the past 6 years I would say.  I have lived at Marshall Street for the past 23 years and have never seen anything like this before, Somerville is one of the dirtiest cities ever.  The tenants are not clean, the absent landlords dont care, the business do not have their trash picked up as often as they should and they need to sweep around the sidewalks and in back of their buildings and City of Somerville doesnt care what the city looks like.  I have had to hire exterminators every year for the past 4 years.  This is a costly expense to me and to my neighbors.     When a landlord does nothing about roaches and rodents the tenant and the City take action against the landlord, but when the city doesnt do nothing for the citizens of Somerville should the citizens take action against the city?     I am begging that the City do something about this problem for I cant afford the extra expense, since the city loves to raise my taxes and my water.

Citizen.Name: CARLSON-FLYNN, STEPHANIE
Description: We reported the issue to our landlord (Boston Investments) and had an exterminator (General Environment) come out to our apartment twice.  The first time, the exterminator closed the holes and sprayed poison where mice seemed to have entered our apartment, specifically behind the stove and where the heating units go into the floor in our bedrooms; he also suggested the landlord close holes behind dishwasher and under sink, which landlord then deemed unnecessary.  Exterminator came out second time, 10/2, and put traps around the house since the rodents had been getting into our cabinets in the kitchen, etc.  One trap caught something, which we determined was definitely a rat.  It seems that they are getting in through the holes in our kitchen and possibly original entry point is basement (where there is possible mold) or roof line.  There are two other apartments units in the building that, as far as we know, have not been exterminated.
